Rating: 4
This is a phenominal cake recipe. I have made it several times and had rave reviews. I usually make the frosting with semi-sweet chocolate instead of milk chocolate and everyone still just loves it. It is a rich and chocolaty cake without being "stick to your teeth sweet." It's a very nice mix of chocolates. It is an easy recipe if you follow the instructions. And great to make the day before. Fortunately, I have the article from the Bon Appetite when it was first published and it shows pictures which are quite helpful. Here are some tips for anyone who has had trouble with the recipe. First, make sure all of the ingredients are at room temperature and do not overbeat the cake mix. Absolutely let the cake cook completely before frosting or the frosting will melt. As for the frosting, while you are whisking over the bowl of ice water it is imperative to do this until the frosting is completely cool otherwise you will end up with liquid frosting. As it cools it will lighten in color and become more stiff. Make sure you beat the frosting for 2 minutes at least. It will be a much lighter color and much stiffer but not hard. It should be easy to spread with no dripping. I have added fresh berries on top of the cake, as well as a light dusting of powdered sugar. There are several ways to decorate this and make it unique. Enjoy, it is a fabulous cake!

Rating: 4
I have made a modified version of this cake again and again. Each time I get many compliments and requests for the recipe. The cake is moist and not too sweet. The frosting is sooo delicious! I use a "Bittersweet Chocolate Sauce" instead of the toffee bars. (The recipe is from epicurious) The end product reminds me of "torte" I enjoyed at cafes in Germany. I sift the dry ingredients for the cake. High quality chocolate such as Ghirardelli or Lindt is a must for the cake, sauce and frosting. Follow the directions exactly for the frosting; tranfer from saucepan to stainless bowl and use the larger bowl filled with ice & a little water to cool the frosting. Allow cakes to cool COMPLETELY. Cut each cake horizontally in half. Chocolate sauce should be easy to spread but not runny. (When it's completely cool it'll be like a fudgy ganache; heat up left overs and use as ice cream topping!)Spread first layer with choc. sauce, second with frosting, third with choc. sauce. Frost entire cake. Decorate. Chocolate lovers enjoy!!

